  "text": "After the successful eradication of HK/97 viruses, multiple new genotypes of H5N1 (i.e. A-E and V-Z) emerged in the Hong Kong region in the early 2000s (Guan et al., 2002a, b; Li et al., 2004) , that were characterized by their high pathogenicity for chickens, and also for mice without prior adaptation, and their unusual capacity to spread to the brain [CITATION_1] . These viruses had notably acquired a mutation in the NS segment, resulting in deletion of aa 80-84 in the unstructured region linking the RNA-binding domain (RBD) of NS1 to its effector domain (ED) (Table S1 and data available in the online Supplementary Material). Segment 8 carrying this deletion has since become largely predominant among H5N1 viruses and has also propagated to some non-H5N1 viruses [CITATION_2] (Fig. 1 , Table S2 ).",
